  doi       = {10.1371/journal.pone.0171773},
  url       = {https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0171773},
  publisher = {Public Library of Science},
  abstract  = {Using known-age Antarctic krill (*Euphausia superba*) grown from eggs hatched at two different laboratories, we validate the annual pattern of bands deposited in the eyestalks of krill and determine the absolute age of these animals. Ages two through five years were validated, and these animals ranged from 37.1 to 62.6 mm in total length. The band counts in these individuals were either identical to their absolute ages or differed by only a few months, demonstrating the accuracy of this method. High accuracy and precision between readers and low ageing bias indicate that longitudinal sections of eyestalks can be used to age krill in wild samples and to develop age-based stock assessment models. Archival samples preserved in formalin and stored in ambient conditions were also readable. This method allows retrospective analyses of krill production and growth trends in response to climate variability.}
